{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cc829273-4fde-4be6-85b2-a3c7d6002c47","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>.ips`. Open with any text editor.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open Console → select \"Crash Reports\" in the sidebar to browse them interactively.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically appears in `/cores/`.\n\n4. **`lldb`** — Attach to a running process or load a core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./YourApp\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash reports are usually the quickest path — they include the faulting thread, stack traces, and signal info without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b8b70bd1-2af2-4175-af55-1b7276202f4b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":317,"requestId":"A0D5:35214E:954931:B78225:6A013671"},"id":"7db5eea6-c761-4acf-8487-25ea0335179d","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:53:00.816Z","parentId":"c81f758b-930b-4a80-81b8-5635ea5b7767"}
